    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="111"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Secretary’s Letters, lot 56 D 459, “Memorandums
                    for the President”</note>
                <head>No. 111<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                            State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-19">June 19,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Economic Pressures on Communist China</item>
                </list>
                <p>At a meeting yesterday with <persName corresp="#p_MSRM1">Roger Makins</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d111fn1">British Ambassador to the United States.</note> I
                    emphasized the importance we attached to the maintenance of economic pressures
                    on Communist China as providing a trading ground at a Korean political
                    conference. <persName corresp="#p_MSRM1">Sir Roger</persName> said that he
                    believed his Government would agree to this and referred to a statement along
                    these general lines which he said had been made in Commons by
                        <persName>Thorneycroft</persName>.<note n="2" xml:id="d111fn2">
                        <persName>John E. Thorneycroft</persName>, President of the British Board of
                        Trade.</note> I expressed gratification.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">John Foster Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
